# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: performance-engineering
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] In computer architecture, **Amdahl's law** (or **Amdahl's argument**) is a formula limiting the speedup of a task as resources are added to the system executing that task.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] It is named after computer scientist Gene Amdahl, and was presented at the American Federation of Information Processing Societies (AFIPS) Spring Joint Computer Conference in 1967.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law is often used in parallel computing to predict the theoretical speedup when using multiple processors.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] The ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ is frequently much lower than one might expect.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] So, despite a massive improvement in one section, the overall benefit is quite small.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] In another example, if the programmer optimizes a section that accounts for 99% of the execution time (i.e. ${\text{Time}}_{\text{optimized}}$ of 0.99) with a speedup factor of 100 (i.e. ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{optimized}}$ of 100), the ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ only reaches 50.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] This indicates that half of the potential performance gain ( ${\text{Speedup}}_{\text{overall}}$ will reach 100 if 100% of the execution time is covered) is lost due to the remaining 1% of execution time that was not improved.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] An example is a computer program that processes files.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] A part of that program may scan the directory of the disk and create a list of files internally in memory.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] After that, another part of the program passes each file to a separate thread for processing.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] The part that scans the directory and creates the file list cannot be sped up on a parallel computer, but the part that processes the files can.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] The execution time of the whole task before the improvement of the resources of the system is denoted as T .
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] It includes the execution time of the part that would not benefit from the improvement of the resources and the execution time of the one that would benefit from it.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] The fraction of the execution time of the task that would benefit from the improvement of the resources is denoted by p .
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] The one concerning the part that would not benefit from it is therefore $1-p$ .
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] It is the execution of the part that benefits from the improvement of the resources that is accelerated by the factor s after the improvement of the resources.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] If 30% of the execution time may be the subject of a speedup, *p* will be 0.3; if the improvement makes the affected part twice as fast, *s* will be 2.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] For example, assume that we are given a serial task which is split into four consecutive parts, whose percentages of execution time are *p*1 = 0.11, *p*2 = 0.18, *p*3 = 0.23, and *p*4 = 0.48 respectively.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Then we are told that the 1st part is not sped up, so *s*1 = 1, while the 2nd part is sped up 5 times, so *s*2 = 5, the 3rd part is sped up 20 times, so *s*3 = 20, and the 4th part is sped up 1.6 times, so *s*4 = 1.6.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Notice how the 5 times and 20 times speedup on the 2nd and 3rd parts respectively don't have much effect on the overall speedup when the 4th part (48% of the execution time) is accelerated by only 1.6 times.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Therefore, making part *A* to run 2 times faster is better than making part *B* to run 5 times faster.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] When $s=1$ , we have $S_{\text{latency}}(O,s)=1$ , meaning that the speedup is measured with respect to the execution time after the non-parallelizable part is optimized.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Next, we consider the case wherein the non-parallelizable part is reduced by a factor of $O'$ , and the parallelizable part is correspondingly increased.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law is often conflated with the law of diminishing returns, whereas only a special case of applying Amdahl's law demonstrates the law of diminishing returns.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] If one picks optimally (in terms of the achieved speedup) what is to be improved, then one will see monotonically decreasing improvements as one improves.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] If, however, one picks non-optimally, after improving a sub-optimal component and moving on to improve a more optimal component, one can see an increase in the return.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Note that it is often rational to improve a system in an order that is "non-optimal" in this sense, given that some improvements are more difficult or require larger development time than others.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Amdahl's law does represent the law of diminishing returns if one is considering what sort of return one gets by adding more processors to a machine, if one is running a fixed-size computation that will use all available processors to their capacity.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Each new processor added to the system will add less usable power than the previous one.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] Each time one doubles the number of processors the speedup ratio will diminish, as the total throughput heads toward the limit of 1/(1 − *p*).
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] This analysis neglects other potential bottlenecks such as memory bandwidth and I/O bandwidth.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] If these resources do not scale with the number of processors, then merely adding processors provides even lower returns.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] An implication of Amdahl's law is that to speed up real applications which have both serial and parallel portions, heterogeneous computing techniques are required.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] There are novel speedup and energy consumption models based on a more general representation of heterogeneity, referred to as the normal form heterogeneity, that support a wide range of heterogeneous many-core architectures.
[src:performance-engineering/amdahl-s-law] These modelling methods aim to predict system power efficiency and performance ranges, and facilitates research and development at the hardware and system software levels.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] In computing, a **benchmark** is the act of running a computer program, a set of programs, or other operations, in order to assess the relative performance of an object, normally by running a number of standard tests and trials against it.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] The term *benchmark* is also commonly utilized for the purposes of elaborately designed benchmarking programs themselves.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking is usually associated with assessing performance characteristics of computer hardware, for example, the floating point operation performance of a CPU, but there are circumstances when the technique is also applicable to software.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Software benchmarks are, for example, run against compilers or database management systems (DBMS).
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks provide a method of comparing the performance of various subsystems across different chip/system architectures.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking as a part of continuous integration is called Continuous Benchmarking.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] As computer architecture advanced, it became more difficult to compare the performance of various computer systems simply by looking at their specifications.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Therefore, tests were developed that allowed comparison of different architectures.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks are designed to mimic a particular type of workload on a component or system.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Synthetic benchmarks do this by specially created programs that impose the workload on the component.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Application benchmarks run real-world programs on the system.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] While application benchmarks usually give a much better measure of real-world performance on a given system, synthetic benchmarks are useful for testing individual components, like a hard disk or networking device.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks are particularly important in CPU design, giving processor architects the ability to measure and make tradeoffs in microarchitectural decisions.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] For example, if a benchmark extracts the key algorithms of an application, it will contain the performance-sensitive aspects of that application.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Running this much smaller snippet on a cycle-accurate simulator can give clues on how to improve performance.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Since around 1995, the SPEC collection of benchmarks have become widely used.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Computer companies are known to tune their systems to improve performance on benchmark tests that are not representative of real world usage.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Benchmarks have been improved to more closely mimic real world usage, so that any tuning carries over to application performance.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Software vendors also use benchmarks in their marketing, such as the "benchmark wars" between rival relational database makers in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Companies commonly report only those benchmarks (or aspects of benchmarks) that show their products in the best light.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] They also have been known to mis-represent the significance of benchmarks, again to show their products in the best possible light.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] When performance is critical, the only benchmark that matters is the target environment's application suite.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Features of benchmarking software may include recording/exporting the course of performance to a spreadsheet file, visualization such as drawing line graphs or color-coded tiles, and pausing the process to be able to resume without having to start over.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Benchmarking is not easy and often involves several iterative rounds in order to arrive at predictable, useful conclusions.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Interpretation of benchmarking data is also extraordinarily difficult.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] There are seven vital characteristics for benchmarks.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Representativeness: Benchmark performance metrics should be broadly accepted by industry and academia.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Equity: All systems should be fairly compared.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Repeatability: Benchmark results can be verified.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Cost-effectiveness: Benchmark tests are economical.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Scalability: Benchmark tests should work across systems possessing a range of resources from low to high.
[src:performance-engineering/benchmark-computing] Transparency: Benchmark metrics should be easy to understand.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:performance-engineering/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Latency is physically a consequence of the limited velocity at which any physical interaction can propagate.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The magnitude of this velocity is always less than or equal to the speed of light.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Therefore, every physical system with any physical separation (distance) between cause and effect will experience some sort of latency, regardless of the nature of the stimulation to which it has been exposed.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The precise definition of latency depends on the system being observed or the nature of the simulation.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In communications, the lower limit of latency is determined by the medium being used to transfer information.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In reliable two-way communication systems, latency limits the maximum rate at which information can be transmitted, as there is often a limit on the amount of information that is in-flight at any given moment.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Perceptible latency has a strong effect on user satisfaction and usability in the field of human–machine interaction.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Online games are sensitive to latency (lag), since fast response times to new events occurring during a game session are rewarded while slow response times may carry penalties.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Due to a delay in transmission of game events, a player with a high-latency internet connection may show slow responses in spite of appropriate reaction time.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] This gives players with low-latency connections a technical advantage.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Trading using computers has developed to the point where millisecond improvements in network speeds offer a competitive advantage for financial institutions.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] However, in a non-trivial network, a typical packet will be forwarded over multiple links and gateways, each of which will not begin to forward the packet until it has been completely received.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In such a network, the minimal latency is the sum of the transmission delay of each link, plus the forwarding latency of each gateway.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In practice, minimal latency also includes queuing and processing delays.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Queuing delay occurs when a gateway receives multiple packets from different sources heading toward the same destination.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Since typically only one packet can be transmitted at a time, some of the packets must queue for transmission, incurring additional delay.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Processing delays are incurred while a gateway determines what to do with a newly received packet.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Bufferbloat can also cause increased latency that is an order of magnitude or more.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The combination of propagation, serialization, queuing, and processing delays often produces a complex and variable network latency profile.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Latency limits total throughput in reliable two-way communication systems as described by the bandwidth-delay product.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Latency in optical fiber is largely a function of the speed of light.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] This would equate to a latency of 3.33 μs for every kilometer of path length.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The index of refraction of most fiber optic cables is about 1.5, meaning that light travels about 1.5 times as fast in a vacuum as it does in the cable.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] This works out to about 5.0 μs of latency for every kilometer.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In shorter metro networks, higher latency can be experienced due to extra distance in building risers and cross-connects.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] To calculate the latency of a connection, one has to know the distance traveled by the fiber, which is rarely a straight line, since it has to traverse geographic contours and obstacles, such as roads and railway tracks, as well as other rights-of-way.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Due to imperfections in the fiber, light degrades as it is transmitted through it.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] For distances of greater than 100 kilometers, amplifiers or regenerators are deployed.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Latency introduced by these components needs to be taken into account.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Low Earth orbit is sometimes used to cut this delay, at the expense of more complicated satellite tracking on the ground and requiring more satellites in the satellite constellation to ensure continuous coverage.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Audio latency is the delay between when an audio signal enters and when it emerges from a system.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Potential contributors to latency in an audio system include analog-to-digital conversion, buffering, digital signal processing, transmission time, digital-to-analog conversion and the speed of sound in air.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Video latency refers to the degree of delay between the time a transfer of a video stream is requested and the actual time that transfer begins.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Networks that exhibit relatively small delays are known as low-latency networks, while their counterparts are known as high-latency networks.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Any individual workflow within a system of workflows can be subject to some type of operational latency.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] It may even be the case that an individual system may have more than one type of latency, depending on the type of participant or goal-seeking behavior.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] This is best illustrated by the following two examples involving air travel.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] From the point of view of a passenger, latency can be described as follows.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Suppose John Doe flies from London to New York.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The latency of his trip is the time it takes him to go from his house in England to the hotel he is staying at in New York.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] This is independent of the throughput of the London-New York air link, whether there were 100 passengers a day making the trip or 10000, the latency of the trip would remain the same.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] From the point of view of flight operations personnel, latency can be entirely different.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Consider the staff at the London and New York airports.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Only a limited number of planes are able to make the transatlantic journey, so when one lands, they must prepare it for the return trip as quickly as possible.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] However, cleaning, refueling and loading the cargo can be done at the same time.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Passengers can only be loaded after cleaning is complete.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The people involved in the turnaround are interested only in the time it takes for their individual tasks.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] When all of the tasks are done at the same time, however, it is possible to reduce the latency to the length of the longest task.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] If some steps have prerequisites, it becomes more difficult to perform all steps in parallel.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In the example above, the requirement to clean the plane before loading passengers results in a minimum latency longer than any single task.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Any mechanical process encounters limitations modeled by Newtonian physics.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The behavior of disk drives provides an example of mechanical latency.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Here, it is the time seek time for the actuator arm to be positioned above the appropriate track and then rotational latency for the data encoded on a platter to rotate from its current position to a position under the disk read-and-write head.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Computers run instructions in the context of a process.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In the context of computer multitasking, the execution of the process can be postponed if other processes are also executing.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In addition, the operating system can schedule when to perform the action that the process is commanding.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] For example, suppose a process commands that a computer card's voltage output be set high-low-high-low and so on at a rate of 1000 Hz.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The operating system schedules the process for each transition (high-low or low-high) based on a hardware clock, such as the High Precision Event Timer.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The latency is the delay between the events generated by the hardware clock and the actual transitions of voltage from high to low or low to high.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Many desktop operating systems have performance limitations that create additional latency.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The problem may be mitigated with real-time extensions and patches such as PREEMPT RT.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] On embedded systems, the real-time execution of instructions is often supported by a real-time operating system.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Note that in software systems, benchmarking against *average* and *median* latency can be misleading because a few outliers can distort them.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Instead, software architects and software developers should use "99th percentile".
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In simulation applications, latency refers to the time delay, often measured in milliseconds, between initial input and output clearly discernible to the simulator trainee or simulator subject.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Latency is sometimes also called *transport delay*.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] Some authorities distinguish between latency and transport delay by using the term *latency* in the sense of the extra time delay of a system over and above the reaction time of the vehicle being simulated, but this requires detailed knowledge of the vehicle dynamics and can be controversial.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] In simulators with both visual and motion systems, it is particularly important that the latency of the motion system not be greater than of the visual system, or symptoms of simulator sickness may result.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] This is because, in the real world, motion cues are those of acceleration and are quickly transmitted to the brain, typically in less than 50 milliseconds; this is followed some milliseconds later by a perception of change in the visual scene.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] The visual scene change is essentially one of change of perspective or displacement of objects, such as the horizon, which takes some time to build up to discernible amounts after the initial acceleration that caused the displacement.
[src:performance-engineering/latency-engineering] A simulator should, therefore, reflect the real-world situation by ensuring that the motion latency is equal to or less than that of the visual system and not the other way round.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In programming language theory, **lazy evaluation**, or **call-by-need**, is an evaluation strategy which delays the evaluation of an expression until its value is needed (non-strict evaluation) and which avoids repeated evaluations (by the use of sharing).
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is often combined with memoization, as described in Jon Bentley's *Writing Efficient Programs*.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] If so, the stored result is simply returned.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] If not, the function is evaluated, and another entry is added to the lookup table for reuse.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is difficult to combine with imperative features such as exception handling and input/output, because the order of operations becomes indeterminate.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The opposite of lazy evaluation is eager evaluation, sometimes known as strict evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Eager evaluation is the evaluation strategy employed in most programming languages.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation was introduced for lambda calculus by Christopher Wadsworth.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] For programming languages, it was independently introduced by Peter Henderson and James H.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation is used particularly in functional programming languages.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] When using delayed evaluation, an expression is not evaluated as soon as it gets bound to a variable, but when the evaluator is forced to produce the expression's value.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation is fundamental in big data frameworks such as Apache Spark, where computations on distributed datasets are delayed until results are explicitly needed, allowing for execution optimizations and reduction of unnecessary processing.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation allows control structures to be defined normally, and not as primitives or compile-time techniques.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] These have the usual semantics, i.e., `ifThenElse a b c` evaluates (a), then if and only if (a) evaluates to true does it evaluate (b), otherwise it evaluates (c).
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] That is, exactly one of (b) or (c) will be evaluated.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Similarly, for `EasilyComputed || LotsOfWork`, if the easy part gives **True** the lots of work expression could be avoided.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Finally, when evaluating `SafeToTry && Expression`, if *SafeToTry* is **false** there will be no attempt at evaluating the *Expression*.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Conversely, in an eager language the above definition for `ifThenElse a b c` would evaluate (a), (b), and (c) regardless of the value of (a).
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] This is not the desired behavior, as (b) or (c) may have side effects, take a long time to compute, or throw errors.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] It is usually possible to introduce user-defined lazy control structures in eager languages as functions, though they may depart from the language's syntax for eager evaluation: Often the involved code bodies need to be wrapped in a function value, so that they are executed only when called.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Delayed evaluation has the advantage of being able to create calculable infinite lists without infinite loops or size matters interfering in computation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The actual values are only computed when needed.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] For example, one could create a function that creates an infinite list (often called a *stream*) of Fibonacci numbers.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The calculation of the *n*-th Fibonacci number would be merely the extraction of that element from the infinite list, forcing the evaluation of only the first n members of the list.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In the function numberFromInfiniteList, the value of infinity is an infinite range, but until an actual value (or more specifically, a specific value at a certain index) is needed, the list is not evaluated, and even then, it is only evaluated as needed (i.e., only to the desired index).
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Provided the programmer is careful, the program completes normally.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell syntax, "`:`" prepends an element to a list, `tail` returns a list without its first element, and `zipWith` uses a specified function (in this case addition) to combine corresponding elements of two lists to produce a third.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In computer windowing systems, the painting of information to the screen is driven by *expose events* which drive the display code at the last possible moment.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] By doing this, windowing systems avoid computing unnecessary display content updates.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Another example of laziness in modern computer systems is copy-on-write page allocation or demand paging, where memory is allocated only when a value stored in that memory is changed.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Laziness can be useful for high performance scenarios.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] An example is the Unix mmap function, which provides *demand driven* loading of pages from disk, so that only those pages actually touched are loaded into memory, and unneeded memory is not allocated.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] MATLAB implements *copy on edit*, where arrays which are copied have their actual memory storage replicated only when their content is changed, possibly leading to an *out of memory* error when updating an element afterwards instead of during the copy operation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The number of beta reductions to reduce a lambda term with call-by-need is not larger than the number needed by call-by-value or call-by-name reduction.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Call-by-need embodies two optimizations - never repeat work (similar to call-by-value), and never perform unnecessary work (similar to call-by-name).
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also lead to reduction in memory footprint, since values are created when needed.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In practice, lazy evaluation may cause significant performance issues compared to eager evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] For example, on modern computer architectures, delaying a computation and performing it later is slower than performing it immediately .
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] This can be alleviated through strictness analysis.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Lazy evaluation can also introduce memory leaks due to unevaluated expressions.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Some programming languages delay evaluation of expressions by default, and some others provide functions or special syntax to delay evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In KRC, Miranda, and Haskell, evaluation of function arguments is delayed by default.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In many other languages, evaluation can be delayed by explicitly suspending the computation using special syntax (as with Scheme's "`delay`" and "`force`" and OCaml's "`lazy`" and "`Lazy.force`") or, more generally, by wrapping the expression in a thunk.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In lazy programming languages such as Haskell, although the default is to evaluate expressions only when they are demanded, it is possible in some cases to make code more eager—or conversely, to make it more lazy again after it has been made more eager.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] This can be done by explicitly coding something which forces evaluation (which may make the code more eager) or avoiding such code (which may make the code more lazy).
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] *Strict* evaluation usually implies eagerness, but they are technically different concepts.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] However, there is an optimisation implemented in some compilers called strictness analysis, which, in some cases, allows the compiler to infer that a value will always be used.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In such cases, this may render the programmer's choice of whether to force that particular value or not, irrelevant, because strictness analysis will force strict evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In Haskell, marking constructor fields strict means that their values will always be demanded immediately.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The `seq` function can also be used to demand a value immediately and then pass it on, which is useful if a constructor field should generally be lazy.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] However, neither of these techniques implements *recursive* strictness—for that, a function called `deepSeq` was invented.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Also, pattern matching in Haskell 98 is strict by default, so the `~` qualifier has to be used to make it lazy.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In C++, the `std::ranges` library uses lazy range adaptors.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In Java, lazy evaluation can be done by using objects that have a method to evaluate them when the value is needed.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The body of this method must contain the code required to perform this evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Since the introduction of lambda expressions in Java SE8, Java has supported a compact notation for this.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The `Lazy` interface with its `eval()` method is equivalent to the `Supplier` interface with its `get()` method in the `java.util.function` library.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Each class that implements the `Lazy` interface must provide an `eval` method, and instances of the class may carry whatever values the method needs to accomplish lazy evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In the above, the variable a initially refers to a lazy integer object created by the lambda expression `() -> 1`.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Evaluating this lambda expression is similar to constructing a new instance of an anonymous class that implements `Lazy<Integer>` with an eval method returning 1.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Each iteration of the loop links a to a new object created by evaluating the lambda expression inside the loop.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Each of these objects holds a reference to another lazy object, b, and has an eval method that calls `b.eval()` twice and returns the sum.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The variable b is needed here to meet Java's requirement that variables referenced from within a lambda expression be effectively final.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] This is an inefficient program because this implementation of lazy integers does not memoize the result of previous calls to eval.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] It also involves considerable autoboxing and unboxing.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] What may not be obvious is that, at the end of the loop, the program has constructed a linked list of 11 objects and that all of the actual additions involved in computing the result are done in response to the call to `a.eval()` on the final line of code.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] This call recursively traverses the list to perform the necessary additions.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] This allows the previous example to be rewritten to be far more efficient.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] Java's lambda expressions are just syntactic sugar.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In JavaScript, lazy evaluation can be simulated by using a generator.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] You can run this example yourself by going to the Kotlin Playground.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] To verify that the program lazily loaded `isThePizzaReady` instead of initializing it beforehand as true we need to check the output of the program.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] As we can see when the program reads from `isThePizzaReady` it prints out a statement we put inside the lazy code block on line 4.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The statement on line 4 does not execute more than once.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x the `range()` function computes a list of integers.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In Python 3.x the `range()` function returns a generator which computes elements of the list on demand.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] This change to lazy evaluation saves execution time for large ranges which may never be fully referenced and memory usage for large ranges where only one or a few elements are needed at any time.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In Python 2.x is possible to use a function called `xrange()` which returns an object that generates the numbers in the range on demand.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The advantage of `xrange` is that generated object will always take the same amount of memory.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] From version 2.2 forward, Python manifests lazy evaluation by implementing iterators (lazy sequences) unlike tuple or list sequences.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] , the first element '0' is printed when need arises.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In the .NET framework, it is possible to do lazy evaluation using the class `System.Lazy<T>`.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] The class can be easily exploited in F# using the `lazy` keyword, while the `force` method will force the evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] There are also specialized collections like `Microsoft.FSharp.Collections.Seq` that provide built-in support for lazy evaluation.
[src:performance-engineering/lazy-evaluation] In C# and VB.NET, the class `System.Lazy<T>` is directly used.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] In computer science, **locality of reference**, also known as the **principle of locality**, is the tendency of a processor to access the same set of memory locations repetitively over a short period of time.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] There are two basic types of reference locality – temporal and spatial locality.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Temporal locality refers to the reuse of specific data and/or resources within a relatively small time duration.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Spatial locality (also termed *data locality*) refers to the use of data elements within relatively close storage locations.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Sequential locality, a special case of spatial locality, occurs when data elements are arranged and accessed linearly, such as traversing the elements in a one-dimensional array.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Locality is a type of predictable behavior that occurs in computer systems.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Systems which exhibit strong *locality of reference* are good candidates for performance optimization through the use of techniques such as the caching, prefetching for memory and advanced branch predictors of a processor core.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] When the matrix size is small, performance differences between traversal methods may appear minimal because the entire dataset fits inside the processor cache.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] However, as matrix dimensions increase, the access pattern becomes a critical factor, since non-sequential traversals generate significantly more cache misses and RAM accesses, reducing overall computational efficiency.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] In order to benefit from temporal and spatial locality, which occur frequently, most of the information storage systems are hierarchical.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Equidistant locality is usually supported by a processor's diverse nontrivial increment instructions.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] For branch locality, contemporary processors have sophisticated branch predictors, and on the basis of this prediction the memory manager of the processor tries to collect and preprocess the data of plausible alternatives.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] These reasons are either goals to achieve or circumstances to accept, depending on the aspect.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] If most of the time the substantial portion of the references aggregate into clusters, and if the shape of this system of clusters can be well predicted, then it can be used for performance optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] There are several ways to benefit from locality using optimization techniques.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Hierarchical memory is a hardware optimization that takes the benefits of spatial and temporal locality and can be used on several levels of the memory hierarchy.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Paging obviously benefits from temporal and spatial locality.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] A cache is a simple example of exploiting temporal locality, because it is a specially designed, faster but smaller memory area, generally used to keep recently referenced data and data near recently referenced data, which can lead to potential performance increases.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Data elements in a cache do not necessarily correspond to data elements that are spatially close in the main memory; however, data elements are brought into cache one cache line at a time.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] This means that spatial locality is again important: if one element is referenced, a few neighboring elements will also be brought into cache.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Finally, temporal locality plays a role on the lowest level, since results that are referenced very closely together can be kept in the machine registers.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Some programming languages (such as C) allow the programmer to suggest that certain variables be kept in registers.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Data locality is a typical memory reference feature of regular programs (though many irregular memory access patterns exist).
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] It makes the hierarchical memory layout profitable.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] In computers, memory is divided into a hierarchy in order to speed up data accesses.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] The lower levels of the memory hierarchy tend to be slower, but larger.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Thus, a program will achieve greater performance if it uses memory while it is cached in the upper levels of the memory hierarchy and avoids bringing other data into the upper levels of the hierarchy that will displace data that will be used shortly in the future.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] This is an ideal, and sometimes cannot be achieved.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Modern machines tend to read blocks of lower memory into the next level of the memory hierarchy.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] If this displaces used memory, the operating system tries to predict which data will be accessed least (or latest) and move it down the memory hierarchy.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Prediction algorithms tend to be simple to reduce hardware complexity, though they are becoming somewhat more complicated.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] By switching the looping order for `j` and `k`, the speedup in large matrix multiplications becomes dramatic, at least for languages that put contiguous array elements in the last dimension.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] This will not change the mathematical result, but it improves efficiency.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] In this case, "large" means, approximately, more than 100,000 elements in each matrix, or enough addressable memory such that the matrices will not fit in L1 and L2 caches.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] The reason for this speedup is that in the first case, the reads of `A[i][k]` are in cache (since the `k` index is the contiguous, last dimension), but `B[k][j]` is not, so there is a cache miss penalty on `B[k][j]`.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] `C[i][j]` is irrelevant, because it can be hoisted out of the inner loop -- the loop variable there is `k`.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] In the second case, the reads and writes of `C[i][j]` are both in cache, the reads of `B[k][j]` are in cache, and the read of `A[i][k]` can be hoisted out of the inner loop.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Thus, the second example has no cache miss penalty in the inner loop while the first example has a cache penalty.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] On a year 2014 processor, the second case is approximately five times faster than the first case, when written in C and compiled with `gcc -O3`.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Temporal locality can also be improved in the above example by using a technique called blocking.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] The larger matrix can be divided into evenly sized sub-matrices, so that the smaller blocks can be referenced (multiplied) several times while in memory.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Note that this example works for square matrices of dimensions SIZE x SIZE, but it can easily be extended for arbitrary matrices by substituting SIZE_I, SIZE_J and SIZE_K where appropriate.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] The temporal locality of the above solution is provided because a block can be used several times before moving on, so that it is moved in and out of memory less often.
[src:performance-engineering/locality-of-reference] Spatial locality is improved because elements with consecutive memory addresses tend to be pulled up the memory hierarchy together.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] In compiler theory, **loop optimization** is the process of increasing execution speed and reducing the overheads associated with loops.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] It plays an important role in improving cache performance and making effective use of parallel processing capabilities.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Most execution time of a scientific program is spent on loops; as such, many compiler optimization techniques have been developed to make them faster.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Since instructions inside loops can be executed repeatedly, it is frequently not possible to give a bound on the number of instruction executions that will be impacted by a loop optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] This presents challenges when reasoning about the correctness and benefits of a loop optimization, specifically the representations of the computation being optimized and the optimization(s) being performed.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Loop optimization can be viewed as the application of a sequence of specific **loop transformations** (listed below or in *Compiler transformations for high-performance computing*) to the source code or intermediate representation, with each transformation having an associated test for legality.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] A transformation (or sequence of transformations) generally must preserve the temporal sequence of all dependencies if it is to preserve the result of the program (i.e., be a legal transformation).
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Evaluating the benefit of a transformation or sequence of transformations can be quite difficult within this approach, as the application of one beneficial transformation may require the prior use of one or more other transformations that, by themselves, would result in reduced performance.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] The unimodular transformation approach uses a single unimodular matrix to describe the combined result of a sequence of many of the above transformations.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Central to this approach is the view of the set of all executions of a statement within *n* loops as a set of integer points in an *n*-dimensional space, with the points being executed in lexicographical order.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] For example, the executions of a statement nested inside an outer loop with index *i* and an inner loop with index *j* can be associated with the pairs of integers ⁠ $(i,j)$ ⁠.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] The application of a unimodular transformation corresponds to the multiplication of the points within this space by the matrix.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] For example, the interchange of two loops corresponds to the matrix ${\begin{bmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{bmatrix}}$ .
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] A unimodular transformation is legal if it preserves the temporal sequence of all dependencies; measuring the performance impact of a unimodular transformation is more difficult.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Imperfectly nested loops and some transformations (such as tiling) do not fit easily into this framework.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] The polyhedral model handles a wider class of programs and transformations than the unimodular framework.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] The set of executions of a set of statements within a possibly imperfectly nested set of loops is seen as the union of a set of polytopes representing the executions of the statements.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Affine transformations are applied to these polytopes, producing a description of a new execution order.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] The boundaries of the polytopes, the data dependencies, and the transformations are often described using systems of constraints, and this approach is often referred to as a **constraint-based** approach to loop optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] For example, a single statement within an outer loop 'for i := 0 to n' and an inner loop 'for j := 0 to i+2' is executed once for each (i, j) pair such that 0 <= i <= n and 0 <= j <= i+2.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Once again, a transformation is legal if it preserves the temporal sequence of all dependencies.
[src:performance-engineering/loop-optimization] Estimating the benefits of a transformation, or finding the best transformation for a given code on a given computer, remain the subject of ongoing research as of the time of this writing (2010).
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In computing, **memoization** or **memoisation** is an optimization technique used primarily to speed up computer programs.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] It works by storing the results of expensive calls to pure functions, so that these results can be returned quickly should the same inputs occur again.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] It is a type of caching, normally implemented using a hash table, and a typical example of a space–time tradeoff, where the runtime of a program is reduced by increasing its memory usage.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Memoization can be implemented in any programming language, though some languages have built-in support that make it easy for the programmer to memoize a function, and others memoize certain functions by default.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Memoization has also been used in other contexts (and for purposes other than speed gains), such as in simple mutually recursive descent parsing.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In the context of some logic programming languages, memoization is also known as tabling.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The term *memoization* was coined by Donald Michie in 1968 and is derived from the Latin word *memorandum* ('to be remembered'), usually truncated as *memo* in American English, and thus carries the meaning of 'turning [the results of] a function into something to be remembered'.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] While *memoization* might be confused with *memorization* (because they are etymological cognates), *memoization* has a specialized meaning in computing.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] A memoized function, when called with a given set of inputs for the first time, stores the inputs along with the computed results.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Upon subsequent calls with remembered inputs, the function returns the remembered results rather than recomputing them, thus eliminating the cost of a recomputation.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The set of remembered associations may be a fixed-size set controlled by a replacement algorithm or a fixed set, depending on the nature of the function and its use.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] A function can only be memoized if it is referentially transparent; that is, only if calling the function has exactly the same effect as replacing that function call with its return value.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] (Special case exceptions to this restriction exist, however.) While related to lookup tables, since memoization often uses such tables in its implementation, memoization populates its cache of results transparently on the fly, rather than needing them to be supplied in advance.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Memoized functions are optimized for *speed* in exchange for a higher use of computer memory *space*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The time/space "cost" of algorithms has a specific name in computing: *computational complexity*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] All functions have a computational complexity in *time* (i.e. they take time to execute) and in *space*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Although a space–time tradeoff occurs (i.e., space used is speed gained), this differs from some other optimizations that involve time-space trade-off, such as strength reduction, in that memoization is a run-time rather than compile-time optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] For every integer *n* such that `*n* ≥ 0`, the final result of the function `factorial` is invariant; if invoked as `*x* = factorial(3)`, the result is such that *x* will *always* be assigned the value 6.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The non-memoized implementation above, given the nature of the recursive algorithm involved, would require *n + 1* invocations of `factorial` to arrive at a result, and each of these invocations, in turn, has an associated cost in the time it takes the function to return the value computed.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The cost to set up the recursive call stack frame.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The cost to multiply the result of the recursive call to `factorial` by *n*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The cost to store the return result so that it may be used by the calling context.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In a non-memoized implementation, *every* top-level call to `factorial` includes the cumulative cost of steps 2 through 6 proportional to the initial value of *n*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] If it is then called with a number greater than 5, such as 7, only 2 recursive calls will be made (7 and 6), and the value for 5! will have been stored from the previous call.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In this way, memoization allows a function to become more time-efficient the more often it is called, thus resulting in eventual overall speed-up.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] An extreme example of memoization is the Singleton pattern, specifically the implementation of its getter — a function that creates an object upon the first invocation, caches the instance, and returns the same object on all subsequent invocations.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Memoization is heavily used in compilers for functional programming languages, which often use call by name evaluation strategy.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] To avoid overhead with calculating argument values, compilers for these languages heavily use auxiliary functions called thunks to compute the argument values, and memoize these functions to avoid repeated calculations.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] While memoization may be added to functions *internally* and *explicitly* by a computer programmer in much the same way the above memoized version of `factorial` is implemented, referentially transparent functions may also be automatically memoized *externally*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The techniques employed by Peter Norvig have application not only in Common Lisp (the language in which his paper demonstrated automatic memoization), but also in various other programming languages.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Applications of automatic memoization have also been formally explored in the study of term rewriting and artificial intelligence.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In programming languages where functions are first-class objects (such as Lua, Python, or Perl), automatic memoization can be implemented by replacing (at run-time) a function with its calculated value once a value has been calculated for a given set of parameters.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The function that does this value-for-function-object replacement can generically wrap any referentially transparent function.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In order to call an automatically memoized version of `factorial` using the above strategy, rather than calling `factorial` directly, code invokes `memoized-call(factorial)(*n*)`.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Each such call first checks to see if a holder array has been allocated to store results, and if not, attaches that array.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] If no entry exists at the position `values[arguments]` (where `arguments` are used as the key of the associative array), a *real* call is made to `factorial` with the supplied arguments.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Finally, the entry in the array at the key position is returned to the caller.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The above strategy requires *explicit* wrapping at each call to a function that is to be memoized.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In those languages that allow closures, memoization can be effected *implicitly* via a functor factory that returns a wrapped memoized function object in a decorator pattern.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The above example assumes that the function `factorial` has already been defined *before* the call to `construct-memoized-functor` is made.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] From this point forward, `memfact(*n*)` is called whenever the factorial of *n* is desired.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] When a top-down parser tries to parse an ambiguous input with respect to an ambiguous context-free grammar (CFG), it may need an exponential number of steps (with respect to the length of the input) to try all alternatives of the CFG in order to produce all possible parse trees.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] This eventually would require exponential memory space.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The basic idea in Norvig's approach is that when a parser is applied to the input, the result is stored in a memotable for subsequent reuse if the same parser is ever reapplied to the same input.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Richard Frost and Barbara Szydlowski also used memoization to reduce the exponential time complexity of parser combinators, describing the result as a memoizing purely functional top-down backtracking language processor.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Frost showed that basic memoized parser combinators can be used as building blocks to construct complex parsers as executable specifications of CFGs.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Memoization was again explored in the context of parsing in 1995 by Mark Johnson and Jochen Dörre.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In 2002, it was examined in considerable depth by Bryan Ford in the form called packrat parsing.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In 2007, Frost, Hafiz and Callaghan described a top-down parsing algorithm that uses memoization for refraining redundant computations to accommodate any form of ambiguous CFG in polynomial time (Θ(n4) for left-recursive grammars and Θ(n3) for non left-recursive grammars).
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Their top-down parsing algorithm also requires polynomial space for potentially exponential ambiguous parse trees by 'compact representation' and 'local ambiguities grouping'.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Their compact representation is comparable with Tomita's compact representation of bottom-up parsing.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Frost, Hafiz and Callaghan also described the implementation of the algorithm in PADL’08 as a set of higher-order functions (called parser combinators) in Haskell, which enables the construction of directly executable specifications of CFGs as language processors.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The importance of their polynomial algorithm's power to accommodate ‘any form of ambiguous CFG’ with top-down parsing is vital with respect to the syntax and semantics analysis during natural language processing.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The X-SAIGA site has more about the algorithm and implementation details.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] While Norvig increased the *power* of the parser through memoization, the augmented parser was still as time complex as Earley's algorithm, which demonstrates a case of the use of memoization for something other than speed optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Johnson and Dörre demonstrate another such non-speed related application of memoization: the use of memoization to delay linguistic constraint resolution to a point in a parse where sufficient information has been accumulated to resolve those constraints.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] By contrast, in the speed optimization application of memoization, Ford demonstrated that memoization could guarantee that parsing expression grammars could parse in linear time even those languages that resulted in worst-case backtracking behavior.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The key concept here is inherent in the phrase **again descends into *X***.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] The process of looking forward, failing, backing up, and then retrying the next alternative is known in parsing as backtracking, and it is primarily backtracking that presents opportunities for memoization in parsing.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] Let the return value of the function `RuleAcceptsSomeInput` be the length of the input accepted by `Rule`, or 0 if that rule does not accept any input at that offset in the string.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In the above example, one or *many* descents into *X* may occur, allowing for strings such as *xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxbd*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] In fact, there may be *any number* of *x*'s before the *b*.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] While the call to S must recursively descend into X as many times as there are *x*'s, *B* will never have to descend into X at all, since the return value of `RuleAcceptsSomeInput(*X*, 0, *xxxxxxxxxxxxxxxxbd*)` will be 16 (in this particular case).
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] For the same reason, memoized parser algorithms that generate calls to external code (sometimes called a semantic action routine) when a rule matches must use some scheme to ensure that such rules are invoked in a predictable order.
[src:performance-engineering/memoization] This effect can be mitigated by explicit selection of those rules the parser will memoize.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] In software engineering, **profiling** (**program profiling**, **software profiling**) is a form of dynamic program analysis that measures, for example, the space (memory) or time complexity of a program, the usage of particular instructions, or the frequency and duration of function calls.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Most commonly, profiling information serves to aid program optimization, and more specifically, performance engineering.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling is achieved by instrumenting either the program source code or its binary executable form using a tool called a *profiler* (or *code profiler*).
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers may use a number of different techniques, such as event-based, statistical, instrumented, and simulation methods.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers use a wide variety of techniques to collect data, including hardware interrupts, code instrumentation, instruction set simulation, operating system hooks, and performance counters.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Summary profile information is often shown annotated against the source code statements where the events occur, so the size of measurement data is linear to the code size of the program.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] For sequential programs, a summary profile is usually sufficient, but performance problems in parallel programs (waiting for messages or synchronization issues) often depend on the time relationship of events, thus requiring a full trace to get an understanding of what is happening.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] A trace may therefore be initiated at one point in a program and terminated at another point to limit the output.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] This provides the opportunity to switch a trace on or off at any desired point during execution in addition to viewing on-going metrics about the (still executing) program.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] It also provides the opportunity to suspend asynchronous processes at critical points to examine interactions with other parallel processes in more detail.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be applied to an individual method or at the scale of a module or program, to identify performance bottlenecks by making long-running code obvious.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] A profiler can be used to understand code from a timing point of view, with the objective of optimizing it to handle various runtime conditions or various loads.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be ingested by a compiler that provides profile-guided optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profiling results can be used to guide the design and optimization of an individual algorithm; the Krauss matching wildcards algorithm is an example.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers are built into some application performance management systems that aggregate profiling data to provide insight into transaction workloads in distributed applications.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Performance-analysis tools existed on IBM/360 and IBM/370 platforms from the early 1970s, usually based on timer interrupts which recorded the program status word (PSW) at set timer-intervals to detect "hot spots" in executing code.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] This was an early example of sampling (see below).
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] In early 1974 instruction-set simulators permitted full trace and other performance-monitoring features.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profiler-driven program analysis on Unix dates back to 1973, when Unix systems included a basic tool, `prof`, which listed each function and how much of program execution time it used.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] In 1982 `gprof` extended the concept to a complete call graph analysis.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] In 1994, Amitabh Srivastava and Alan Eustace of Digital Equipment Corporation published a paper describing ATOM (Analysis Tools with OM).
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] The ATOM platform converts a program into its own profiler: at compile time, it inserts code into the program to be analyzed.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] That inserted code outputs analysis data.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] This technique - modifying a program to analyze itself - is known as "instrumentation".
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] In 2004 both the `gprof` and ATOM papers appeared on the list of the 50 most influential PLDI papers for the 20-year period ending in 1999.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Flat profilers compute the average call times, from the calls, and do not break down the call times based on the callee or the context.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Call graph profilers show the call times, and frequencies of the functions, and also the call-chains involved based on the callee.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] In some tools full context is not preserved.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Input-sensitive profilers add a further dimension to flat or call-graph profilers by relating performance measures to features of the input workloads, such as input size or input values.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] They generate charts that characterize how an application's performance scales as a function of its input.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers, which are also programs themselves, analyze target programs by collecting information on the target program's execution.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Based on their data granularity, which depends upon how profilers collect information, they are classified as *event-based* or *statistical* profilers.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Profilers interrupt program execution to collect information.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Those interrupts can limit time measurement resolution, which implies that timing results should be taken with a grain of salt.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Basic block profilers report a number of machine clock cycles devoted to executing each line of code, or timing based on adding those together; the timings reported per basic block may not reflect a difference between cache hits and misses.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] A sampling profiler probes the target program's call stack at regular intervals using operating system interrupts.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Sampling profiles are typically less numerically accurate and specific, providing only a statistical approximation, but allow the target program to run at near full speed.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] "The actual amount of error is usually more than one sampling period.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] In practice, sampling profilers can often provide a more accurate picture of the target program's execution than other approaches, as they are not as intrusive to the target program and thus don't have as many side effects (such as on memory caches or instruction decoding pipelines).
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Also since they don't create much overhead, they can detect issues that would otherwise be hidden.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] They are also relatively immune to over-evaluating the cost of small, frequently called routines or 'tight' loops.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] They can show the relative amount of time spent in user mode versus interruptible kernel mode such as system call processing.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Unfortunately, running kernel code to handle the interrupts incurs a minor loss of CPU cycles from the target program, diverts cache usage, and cannot distinguish the various tasks occurring in uninterruptible kernel code (microsecond-range activity) from user code.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Dedicated hardware can do better: ARM Cortex-M3 and some recent MIPS processors' JTAG interfaces have a PCSAMPLE register, which samples the program counter in a truly undetectable manner, allowing non-intrusive collection of a flat profile.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Some commonly used statistical profilers for Java/managed code are SmartBear Software's AQtime and Microsoft's CLR Profiler.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Those profilers also support native code profiling, along with Apple Inc.'s Shark (OSX), OProfile (Linux), Intel VTune and Parallel Amplifier (part of Intel Parallel Studio), and Oracle Performance Analyzer, among others.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] This technique effectively adds instructions to the target program to collect the required information.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Note that instrumenting a program can cause performance changes, and may in some cases lead to inaccurate results and/or heisenbugs.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] The effect will depend on what information is being collected, on the level of timing details reported, and on whether basic block profiling is used in conjunction with instrumentation.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] For example, adding code to count every procedure/routine call will probably have less effect than counting how many times each statement is obeyed.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] A few computers have special hardware to collect information; in this case the impact on the program is minimal.
[src:performance-engineering/profiling-computer-programming] Instrumentation is key to determining the level of control and amount of time resolution available to the profilers.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In computer science, **program optimization**, **code optimization**, or **software optimization** is the process of modifying a software system to make some aspect of it work more efficiently or use fewer resources.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In general, a computer program may be optimized so that it executes more rapidly, or to make it capable of operating with less memory storage or other resources, or draw less power.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Although the term "optimization" is derived from "optimum", achieving a truly optimal system is rare in practice, which is referred to as superoptimization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization typically focuses on improving a system with respect to a specific quality metric rather than making it universally optimal.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] This often leads to trade-offs, where enhancing one metric may come at the expense of another.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] One frequently cited example is the space–time tradeoff, where reducing a program’s execution time can increase its memory consumption.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Conversely, in scenarios where memory is limited, engineers might prioritize a slower algorithm to conserve space.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] There is rarely a single design that can excel in all situations, requiring programmers to prioritize attributes most relevant to the application at hand.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Metrics for software include throughput, latency, volatile memory usage, persistent storage, internet usage, energy consumption, and hardware wear and tear.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Furthermore, achieving absolute optimization often demands disproportionate effort relative to the benefits gained.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Consequently, optimization processes usually slow once sufficient improvements are achieved.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Fortunately, significant gains often occur early in the optimization process, making it practical to stop before reaching diminishing returns.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization can occur at a number of levels.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Typically the higher levels have greater impact, and are harder to change later on in a project, requiring significant changes or a complete rewrite if they need to be changed.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Thus optimization can typically proceed via refinement from higher to lower, with initial gains being larger and achieved with less work, and later gains being smaller and requiring more work.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] However, in some cases overall performance depends on performance of very low-level portions of a program, and small changes at a late stage or early consideration of low-level details can have outsized impact.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Typically some consideration is given to efficiency throughout a project – though this varies significantly – but major optimization is often considered a refinement to be done late, if ever.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] On longer-running projects there are typically cycles of optimization, where improving one area reveals limitations in another, and these are typically curtailed when performance is acceptable or gains become too small or costly.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Best practices for optimization during iterative development cycles include continuous monitoring for performance issues coupled with regular performance testing.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] The degree to which performance changes between prototype and production system, and how amenable it is to optimization, can be a significant source of uncertainty and risk.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] At the highest level, the design may be optimized to make best use of the available resources, given goals, constraints, and expected use/load.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] The architectural design of a system overwhelmingly affects its performance.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, a system that is network latency-bound (where network latency is the main constraint on overall performance) would be optimized to minimize network trips, ideally making a single request (or no requests, as in a push protocol) rather than multiple roundtrips.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Choice of platform and programming language occur at this level, and changing them frequently requires a complete rewrite, though a modular system may allow rewrite of only some component – for example, for a Python program one may rewrite performance-critical sections in C.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In a distributed system, choice of architecture (client-server, peer-to-peer, etc.) occurs at the design level, and may be difficult to change, particularly if all components cannot be replaced in sync (e.g., old clients).
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Given an overall design, a good choice of efficient algorithms and data structures, and efficient implementation of these algorithms and data structures comes next.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] After design, the choice of algorithms and data structures affects efficiency more than any other aspect of the program.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Changes in data structures mapped to a database may require schema migration and other complex software or infrastructure changes.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For algorithms, this primarily consists of ensuring that algorithms are constant O(1), logarithmic O(log *n*), linear O(*n*), or in some cases log-linear O(*n* log *n*) in the input (both in space and time).
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Algorithms with quadratic complexity O(*n*2) fail to scale, and even linear algorithms cause problems if repeatedly called, and are typically replaced with constant or logarithmic if possible.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Beyond asymptotic order of growth, the constant factors matter: an asymptotically slower algorithm may be faster or smaller (because simpler) than an asymptotically faster algorithm when they are both faced with small input, which may be the case that occurs in reality.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Often a hybrid algorithm will provide the best performance, due to this tradeoff changing with size.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A general technique to improve performance is to avoid work.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A good example is the use of a fast path for common cases, improving performance by avoiding unnecessary work.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, using a simple text layout algorithm for Latin text, only switching to a complex layout algorithm for complex scripts, such as Devanagari.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Another important technique is caching, particularly memoization, which avoids redundant computations.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Because of the importance of caching, there are often many levels of caching in a system, which can cause problems from memory use, and correctness issues from stale caches.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Beyond general algorithms and their implementation on an abstract machine, concrete source code level choices can make a significant difference.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, on early C compilers, `while (true)` was slower than `for (;;)` for an unconditional loop, because `while (true)` evaluated `true` and then had a conditional jump which tested if it was true, while `for (;;)` had an unconditional jump.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Some optimizations (such as this one) can nowadays be performed by optimizing compilers.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] This depends on the source language, the target machine language, and the compiler, and can be both difficult to understand or predict and changes over time; this is a key place where understanding of compilers and machine code can improve performance.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Loop-invariant code motion and return value optimization are examples of optimizations that reduce the need for auxiliary variables and can even result in faster performance by avoiding round-about optimizations.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Source-based software distribution systems such as BSD's Ports and Gentoo's Portage can take advantage of this form of optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Use of an optimizing compiler with optimizations enabled tends to ensure that the executable program is optimized at least as much as the compiler can reasonable perform.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] See Optimizing compiler for more details.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] At the lowest level, writing code using an assembly language, designed for a particular hardware platform can produce the most efficient and compact code if the programmer takes advantage of the full repertoire of machine instructions.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Many operating systems used on embedded systems have been traditionally written in assembler code for this reason.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Programs (other than very small programs) are seldom written from start to finish in assembly due to the time and cost involved.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Most are compiled down from a high level language to assembly and hand optimized from there.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] When efficiency and size are less important large parts may be written in a high-level language.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] With more modern optimizing compilers and the greater complexity of recent CPUs, it is harder to write more efficient code than what the compiler generates, and few projects need this "ultimate" optimization step.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Much of the code written today is intended to run on as many machines as possible.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] As a consequence, programmers and compilers don't always take advantage of the more efficient instructions provided by newer CPUs or quirks of older models.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Additionally, assembly code tuned for a particular processor without using such instructions might still be suboptimal on a different processor, expecting a different tuning of the code.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Typically today rather than writing in assembly language, programmers will use a disassembler to analyze the output of a compiler and change the high-level source code so that it can be compiled more efficiently, or understand why it is inefficient.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Just-in-time compilers can produce customized machine code based on run-time data, at the cost of compilation overhead.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] This technique dates to the earliest regular expression engines, and has become widespread with Java HotSpot and V8 for JavaScript.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In some cases adaptive optimization may be able to perform run time optimization exceeding the capability of static compilers by dynamically adjusting parameters according to the actual input or other factors.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Profile-guided optimization is an ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation optimization technique based on run time profiles, and is similar to a static "average case" analog of the dynamic technique of adaptive optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Self-modifying code can alter itself in response to run time conditions in order to optimize code; this was more common in assembly language programs.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Some CPU designs can perform some optimizations at run time.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Some examples include out-of-order execution, speculative execution, instruction pipelines, and branch predictors.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Compilers can help the program take advantage of these CPU features, for example through instruction scheduling.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Code optimization can be also broadly categorized as platform-dependent and platform-independent techniques.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] While the latter ones are effective on most or all platforms, platform-dependent techniques use specific properties of one platform, or rely on parameters depending on the single platform or even on the single processor.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Writing or producing different versions of the same code for different processors might therefore be needed.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For instance, in the case of compile-level optimization, platform-independent techniques are generic techniques (such as loop unrolling, reduction in function calls, memory efficient routines, reduction in conditions, etc.), that impact most CPU architectures in a similar way.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A great example of platform-independent optimization has been shown with inner for loop, where it was observed that a loop with an inner for loop performs more computations per unit time than a loop without it or one with an inner while loop.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Generally, these serve to reduce the total instruction path length required to complete the program and/or reduce total memory usage during the process.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Computational tasks can be performed in several different ways with varying efficiency.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A more efficient version with equivalent functionality is known as a strength reduction.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] The optimization, sometimes performed automatically by an optimizing compiler, is to select a method (algorithm) that is more computationally efficient, while retaining the same functionality.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] See algorithmic efficiency for a discussion of some of these techniques.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] However, a significant improvement in performance can often be achieved by removing extraneous functionality.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization is not always an obvious or intuitive process.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In the example above, the "optimized" version might actually be slower than the original version if *N* were sufficiently small and the particular hardware happens to be much faster at performing addition and looping operations than multiplication and division.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In some cases, however, optimization relies on using more elaborate algorithms, making use of "special cases" and special "tricks" and performing complex trade-offs.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A "fully optimized" program might be more difficult to comprehend and hence may contain more faults than unoptimized versions.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Beyond eliminating obvious antipatterns, some code level optimizations decrease maintainability.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization will generally focus on improving just one or two aspects of performance: execution time, memory usage, disk space, bandwidth, power consumption or some other resource.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] This will usually require a trade-off – where one factor is optimized at the expense of others.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, increasing the size of cache improves run time performance, but also increases the memory consumption.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Other common trade-offs include code clarity and conciseness.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] There are instances where the programmer performing the optimization must decide to make the software better for some operations but at the cost of making other operations less efficient.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] These trade-offs may sometimes be of a non-technical nature – such as when a competitor has published a benchmark result that must be beaten in order to improve commercial success but comes perhaps with the burden of making normal usage of the software less efficient.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Such changes are sometimes jokingly referred to as *pessimizations*.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization may include finding a bottleneck in a system – a component that is the limiting factor on performance.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In terms of code, this will often be a hot spot – a critical part of the code that is the primary consumer of the needed resource – though it can be another factor, such as I/O latency or network bandwidth.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In computer science, resource consumption often follows a form of power law distribution, and the Pareto principle can be applied to resource optimization by observing that 80% of the resources are typically used by 20% of the operations.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In software engineering, it is often a better approximation that 90% of the execution time of a computer program is spent executing 10% of the code (known as the 90/10 law in this context).
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A performance profiler can be used to narrow down decisions about which functionality fits which conditions.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Performance profiling therefore provides not only bottleneck detection but rather a variety of methods for optimization guidance.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Empirical algorithmics is the practice of using empirical methods, typically performance profiling, to study the behavior of algorithms, for developer understanding that may lead to human-planned optimizations.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Profile-guided optimization is the machine-driven use of profiling data as input to an optimizing compiler or interpreter.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Some programming languages are associated with tools for profile-guided optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Some performance profiling methods emphasize enhancements based on cache utilization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Other benefits of performance profiling may include improved resource management and an enhanced user experience.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In some cases, adding more memory can help to make a program run faster.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, a filtering program will commonly read each line and filter and output that line immediately.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] This only uses enough memory for one line, but performance is typically poor, due to the latency of each disk read.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Caching the result is similarly effective, though also requiring larger memory use.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Typically, optimization involves choosing the best overall algorithms and data structures.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Frequently, algorithmic improvements can cause performance improvements of several orders of magnitude instead of micro-optimizations, which rarely improve performance by more than a few percent.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] If one waits to optimize until the end of the development cycle, then changing the algorithm could require a significant rewrite.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Frequently, micro-optimization can reduce readability and complicate programs or systems.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] That can make programs more difficult to maintain and debug.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] "Premature optimization" is often used as a rallying cry against all optimization in all situations for all purposes.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Frequently, Clean Code causes code to be more complicated than simpler more efficient code.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] When deciding what to optimize, Amdahl's Law should be used to proritize parts based on the actual time spent in a certain part, which is not always clear from looking at the code without a performance analysis.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In practice, it is often necessary to keep performance goals in mind when first designing software, yet programmers must balance various tradeoffs.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Development cost is significant, and hardware is fast.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Modern compilers are efficient enough that the intended performance increases sometimes fail to materialize.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Since compilers perform many automatic optimizations, some optimizations may yield an identical executable.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Also, sometimes hardware may reduce the impact of micro-optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, hardware may cache data that is cached at a software level.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization during code development using macros takes on different forms in different languages.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In some procedural languages, such as C and C++, macros are implemented using token substitution.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Nowadays, inline functions can be used as a type safe alternative in many cases.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In both cases, the inlined function body can then undergo further compile-time optimizations by the compiler, including constant folding, which may move some computations to compile time.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In many functional programming languages, macros are implemented using parse-time substitution of parse trees/abstract syntax trees, which it is claimed makes them safer to use.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Since in many cases interpretation is used, that is one way to ensure that such computations are only performed at parse-time, and sometimes the only way.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Lisp originated this style of macro, and such macros are often called "Lisp-like macros".
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A similar effect can be achieved by using template metaprogramming in C++.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In both cases, work is moved to compile-time.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Additionally, C macros do not directly support recursion or iteration, so are not Turing complete.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] As with any optimization, however, it is often difficult to predict where such tools will have the most impact before a project is complete.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization can be automated by compilers or performed by programmers.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Gains are usually limited for local optimization, and larger for global optimizations.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Usually, the most powerful optimization is to find a superior algorithm.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimizing a whole system is usually undertaken by programmers because it is too complex for automated optimizers.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In this situation, programmers or system administrators explicitly change code so that the overall system performs better.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Although it can produce better efficiency, it is far more expensive than automated optimizations.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Since many parameters influence the program performance, the program optimization space is large.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Meta-heuristics and machine learning are used to address the complexity of program optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Use a profiler (or performance analyzer) to find the sections of the program that are taking the most resources – the *bottleneck*.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Programmers sometimes believe they have a clear idea of where the bottleneck is, but intuition is frequently wrong.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimizing an unimportant piece of code will typically do little to help the overall performance.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] When the bottleneck is localized, optimization usually starts with a rethinking of the algorithm used in the program.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] More often than not, a particular algorithm can be specifically tailored to a particular problem, yielding better performance than a generic algorithm.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, the task of sorting a huge list of items is usually done with a quicksort routine, which is one of the most efficient generic algorithms.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] But if some characteristic of the items is exploitable (for example, they are already arranged in some particular order), a different method can be used, or even a custom-made sort routine.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] After the programmer is reasonably sure that the best algorithm is selected, code optimization can start.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Loops can be unrolled (for lower loop overhead, although this can often lead to *lower* speed if it overloads the CPU cache), data types as small as possible can be used, integer arithmetic can be used instead of floating-point, and so on.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Performance bottlenecks can be due to language limitations rather than algorithms or data structures used in the program.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Sometimes, a critical part of the program can be re-written in a different programming language that gives more direct access to the underlying machine.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] For example, it is common for very high-level languages like Python to have modules written in C for greater speed.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Programs already written in C can have modules written in assembly.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Programs written in D can use the inline assembler.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Rewriting sections "pays off" in these circumstances because of a general "rule of thumb" known as the 90/10 law, which states that 90% of the time is spent in 10% of the code, and only 10% of the time in the remaining 90% of the code.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] So, putting intellectual effort into optimizing just a small part of the program can have a huge effect on the overall speed – if the correct part(s) can be located.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Manual optimization sometimes has the side effect of undermining readability.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Thus code optimizations should be carefully documented (preferably using in-line comments), and their effect on future development evaluated.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] The program that performs an automated optimization is called an **optimizer**.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Most optimizers are embedded in compilers and operate during compilation.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimizers can often tailor the generated code to specific processors.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Today, automated optimizations are almost exclusively limited to compiler optimization.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] However, because compiler optimizations are usually limited to a fixed set of rather general optimizations, there is considerable demand for optimizers which can accept descriptions of problem and language-specific optimizations, allowing an engineer to specify custom optimizations.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Tools that accept descriptions of optimizations are called program transformation systems and are beginning to be applied to real software systems such as C++.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Some high-level languages (Eiffel, Esterel) optimize their programs by using an intermediate language.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Grid computing or distributed computing aims to optimize the whole system, by moving tasks from computers with high usage to computers with idle time.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Sometimes, the time taken to undertake optimization therein itself may be an issue.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimizing existing code usually does not add new features, and worse, it might add new bugs in previously working code (as any change might).
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Because manually optimized code might sometimes have less "readability" than unoptimized code, optimization might impact maintainability of it as well.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Optimization comes at a price and it is important to be sure that the investment is worthwhile.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] An automatic optimizer (or optimizing compiler, a program that performs code optimization) may itself have to be optimized, either to further improve the efficiency of its target programs or else speed up its own operation.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] A compilation performed with optimization "turned on" usually takes longer, although this is usually only a problem when programs are quite large.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] In particular, for just-in-time compilers the performance of the run time compile component, executing together with its target code, is the key to improving overall execution speed.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Sometimes, "optimizations" may hurt performance.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Concurrency and parallelism cause significant overhead performance cost and possibly increased energy usage.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Keep in mind that C code rarely uses explicit multiprocessing, yet it typically runs faster than any other programming language.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Disk caching, paging, and swapping often cause significant increases to energy usage and hardware wear and tear.
[src:performance-engineering/program-optimization] Running processes in the background to improve startup time slows down all other processes.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] A **space–time trade-off** (also known as **time–memory trade-off** or **the algorithmic space-time continuum**) in computer science is a trade-off where an algorithm or program increased space usage with decreased time.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Here, *space* refers to the data storage consumed in performing a given task (RAM, HDD, etc.), and *time* refers to the time consumed in performing a given task (computation time or response time).
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] The utility of a given space–time tradeoff is affected by related fixed and variable costs (of, e.g., CPU speed, storage space), and is subject to diminishing returns.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Biological usage of time–memory tradeoffs can be seen in the earlier stages of animal behavior.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Using stored knowledge or encoding stimuli reactions as "instincts" in the DNA avoids the need for "calculation" in time-critical situations.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] More specific to computers, lookup tables have been implemented since the very earliest operating systems.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] In 1980 Martin Hellman first proposed using a time–memory tradeoff for cryptanalysis.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] A common situation is an algorithm involving a lookup table: an implementation can include the entire table, which reduces computing time, but increases the amount of memory needed, or it can compute table entries as needed, increasing computing time, but reducing memory requirements.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Database Management Systems offer the capability to create database index data structures.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Indexes improve the speed of lookup operations at the cost of additional space.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Without indexes, time-consuming full table scan operations are sometimes required to locate desired data.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] A space–time trade off can be applied to the problem of data storage.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] If data is stored uncompressed, it takes more space but access takes less time than if the data were stored compressed (since compressing the data reduces the amount of space it takes, but it takes time to run the decompression algorithm).
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Depending on the particular instance of the problem, either way is practical.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] There are also rare instances where it is possible to directly work with compressed data, such as in the case of compressed bitmap indices, where it is faster to work with compression than without compression.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Storing only the SVG source of a vector image and rendering it as a bitmap image every time the page is requested would be trading time for space; more time used, but less space.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Rendering the image when the page is changed and storing the rendered images would be trading space for time; more space used, but less time.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] This technique is more generally known as caching.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] Larger code size can be traded for higher program speed when applying loop unrolling.
[src:performance-engineering/space-time-tradeoff] This technique makes the code longer for each iteration of a loop, but saves the computation time required for jumping back to the beginning of the loop at the end of each iteration.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The **aggregate throughput** is the sum of the data rates that are delivered over all channels in a network.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Throughput represents digital bandwidth consumption.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The throughput of a communication system may be affected by various factors, including the limitations of the underlying physical medium, available processing power of the system components, end-user behavior, etc.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] When taking various protocol overheads into account, the useful rate of the data transfer can be significantly lower than the maximum achievable throughput; the useful part is usually referred to as goodput.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Users of telecommunications devices, systems designers, and researchers into communication theory are often interested in knowing the expected performance of a system.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] From a user perspective, this is often phrased as either "which device will get my data there most effectively for my needs?", or "which device will deliver the most data per unit cost?".
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Systems designers often select the most effective architecture or design constraints for a system, which drive its final performance.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In most cases, the benchmark of what a system is capable of, or its *maximum performance* is what the user or designer is interested in.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The term *maximum throughput* is frequently used when discussing end-user maximum throughput tests.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Maximum throughput is essentially synonymous with digital bandwidth capacity.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Four different values are relevant in the context of maximum throughput are used in comparing the *upper limit* conceptual performance of multiple systems.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] They are *maximum theoretical throughput*, *maximum achievable throughput*, *peak measured throughput*, and *maximum sustained throughput*.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] These values represent different qualities, and care must be taken that the same definitions are used when comparing different *maximum throughput* values.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Each bit must carry the same amount of information if throughput values are to be compared.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Data compression can significantly alter throughput calculations, including generating values exceeding 100% in some cases.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] If the communication is mediated by several links in series with different bit rates, the maximum throughput of the overall link is lower than or equal to the lowest bit rate.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The lowest value link in the series is referred to as the bottleneck.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is closely related to the channel capacity of the system, and is the maximum possible quantity of data that can be transmitted under ideal circumstances.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In some cases, this number is reported as equal to the channel capacity, though this can be deceptive, as only non-packetized systems technologies can achieve this.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Maximum theoretical throughput is more accurately reported taking into account format and specification overhead with best-case assumptions.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The **asymptotic throughput** (less formal **asymptotic bandwidth**) for a packet-mode communication network is the value of the maximum throughput function, when the incoming network load approaches infinity, either due to a message size, or the number of data sources.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] As with other bit rates and data bandwidths, the asymptotic throughput is measured in bits per second (bit/s) or (rarely) bytes per second (B/s), where 1 B/s is 8 bit/s.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Decimal prefixes are used, meaning that 1 Mbit/s is 1000000 bit/s.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Asymptotic throughput is usually estimated by sending or simulating a very large message (sequence of data packets) through the network, using a greedy source and no flow control mechanism (i.e., UDP rather than TCP), and measuring the volume of data received at the destination node.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Traffic load between other sources may reduce this maximum network path throughput.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Alternatively, a large number of sources and sinks may be modeled, with or without flow control, and the aggregate maximum network throughput measured (the sum of traffic reaching its destinations).
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] A well-known application of asymptotic throughput is in modeling point-to-point communication where message latency $T(N)$ is modeled as a function of message length N as $T(N)=(M+N)/A$ where A is the asymptotic bandwidth and M is the half-peak length.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] As well as its use in general network modeling, asymptotic throughput is used in modeling performance on massively parallel computer systems, where system operation is highly dependent on communication overhead, as well as processor performance.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In these applications, asymptotic throughput is used modeling which includes the number of processors, so that both the latency and the asymptotic throughput are functions of the number of processors.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Where asymptotic throughput is a theoretical or calculated capacity, *peak measured throughput* is throughput measured on a real implemented system, or on a simulated system.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The value is the throughput measured over a short period of time; mathematically, this is the limit taken with respect to throughput as time approaches zero.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] This term is synonymous with *instantaneous throughput*.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] This number is useful for systems that rely on burst data transmission; however, for systems with a high duty cycle, this is less likely to be a useful measure of system performance.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Maximum sustained throughput is the throughput averaged or integrated over a long time.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] For networks under constant load, this is likely to be the most accurate indicator of system performance.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The maximum throughput is defined as the asymptotic throughput when the load is large.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In packet-switched networks while packet loss is not occurring, the load and the throughput always are equal.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The maximum throughput may be defined as the minimum load in bit/s that causes packet loss or causes the latency to become unstable and increase towards infinity.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Throughput is sometimes normalized and measured in percentage, but normalization may cause confusion regarding what the percentage is related to.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] *Channel utilization*, *channel efficiency* and *packet drop rate* in percentage are less ambiguous terms.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The channel efficiency, also known as bandwidth utilization efficiency, is the percentage of the net bit rate (in bit/s) of a digital communication channel that goes to the achieved throughput.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] For example, if the throughput is 70 Mbit/s over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection, the channel efficiency is 70%.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Channel utilization includes both the data bits and the transmission overhead in the channel.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The transmission overhead consists of preamble sequences, frame headers and acknowledgment packets.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In a simplistic approach, channel efficiency can be equal to channel utilization assuming that acknowledge packets are zero-length and that the communications provider will not see any bandwidth relative to retransmissions or headers.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Therefore, certain texts mark a difference between channel utilization and protocol efficiency.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] For example, the maximum frame size in Ethernet is 1526 bytes: up to 1500 bytes for the payload, eight bytes for the preamble, 14 bytes for the header, and 4 bytes for the trailer.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] An additional minimum interframe gap corresponding to 12 bytes is inserted after each frame.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] This corresponds to a maximum channel utilization of 1526 / (1526 + 12) × 100% = 99.22%, or a maximum channel use of 99.22 Mbit/s inclusive of Ethernet datalink layer protocol overhead over a 100 Mbit/s Ethernet connection.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The maximum throughput or channel efficiency is then 1500 / (1526 + 12) = 97.5%, exclusive of the Ethernet protocol overhead.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The throughput of a communication system will be limited by a number of factors.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The maximum achievable throughput (the channel capacity) is affected by the bandwidth in hertz and signal-to-noise ratio of the analog physical medium.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Limited current drive capability in communications equipment can limit the effective signal-to-noise ratio for high capacitance links.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Despite the conceptual simplicity of digital information, all electrical signals traveling over wires are analog.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The analog limitations of wires or wireless systems inevitably provide an upper bound on the amount of information that can be sent.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The dominant equation here is the Shannon–Hartley theorem, and analog limitations of this type can be understood as factors that affect either the analog bandwidth of a signal or as factors that affect the signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The bandwidth of twisted pair cabling used by Ethernet is limited to approximately 1 GHz, and PCB traces are limited by a similar amount.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Digital systems refer to the *knee frequency*, the amount of time for the digital voltage to rise from 10% of a nominal digital 0 to a nominal digital 1 or vice versa.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Large data loads that require processing impose data processing requirements on hardware.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] For example, a gateway router must examine and perform routing table lookups on billions of packets per second.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] CSMA/CD and CSMA/CA backoff waiting time and frame retransmissions after detected collisions slows transmissions.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] This may occur in Ethernet bus networks and hub networks, as well as in wireless networks.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Flow control, for example, in the Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) protocol, affects the throughput if the bandwidth-delay product is larger than the TCP window.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In that case, the sending computer must wait for acknowledgement of the data packets before it can send more packets.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] TCP congestion avoidance controls the data rate.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] A so-called *slow start* occurs in the beginning of a file transfer, and after packet drops caused by router congestion or bit errors in, for example, wireless links.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Ensuring that multiple users can harmoniously share a single communications link requires some kind of equitable sharing of the link.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] If a communication link offering data rate *R* is shared by *N* active users, ideally, every user can typically achieve a throughput of approximately *R/N*.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Network schedulers in routers and switches ultimately determine how bandwidth is shared.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] If fair queuing is not provided, users that send large packets will get higher bandwidth.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Some users may be prioritized in a weighted fair queuing (WFQ) algorithm if differentiated or guaranteed quality of service (QoS) is provided.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In some communications systems, such as satellite networks, only a finite number of channels may be available to a given user at a given time.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Channels are assigned either through preassignment or through Demand Assigned Multiple Access (DAMA).
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In these cases, throughput is quantized per channel, and unused capacity on partially utilized channels is lost.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The maximum throughput is often an unreliable measurement of effective bandwidth, for example the file transmission data rate in bits per seconds.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The achieved throughput is often lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Protocol overhead affects the effective bandwidth.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In schemes that include forward error correction codes, the redundant error code is normally excluded from the throughput.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] An example in modem communication, where the throughput is typically measured in the interface between the Point-to-Point Protocol (PPP) and the circuit-switched modem connection.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In this case, the maximum throughput is often called net bit rate or useful bit rate.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] To determine the actual data rate of a network or connection, the goodput measurement definition may be used.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] For example, in file transmission, the goodput corresponds to the file size (in bits) divided by the file transmission time.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] The goodput is the amount of useful information that is delivered per second to the application layer protocol.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Dropped packets or packet retransmissions, as well as protocol overhead, are excluded.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Because of that, the goodput is lower than the maximum throughput.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Often, a block in a data flow diagram has a single input and a single output, and operates on discrete packets of information.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Examples of such blocks are fast Fourier transform modules or binary multipliers.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Because the units of throughput (e.g., messages per second) are the reciprocal of the unit for propagation delay (e.g., seconds per message), throughput can be used to relate a computational block to a communications channel, simplifying system analysis.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] In wireless networks or cellular systems, the system spectral efficiency in bit/s/Hz/area, bit/s/Hz/site or bit/s/Hz/cell units, is the maximum aggregate throughput divided by the analog bandwidth and some measure of the system coverage area.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Throughput over analog channels is determined by the modulation scheme, the signal-to-noise ratio, and the available bandwidth.
[src:performance-engineering/throughput] Since throughput is normally defined in terms of quantified digital data, the term *throughput* is not normally used; the term *bandwidth* is more often used instead.
